column1: File:Ted Nasmith - Elves in the Woody End.jpg - Elves in the Woody End
Woody End was an upland wooded region of the Eastfarthing of the Shire
column2: lying between the Green Hill Country on the west and the Marish on the east.  Its woods were the sources of the Stock-brook and the Thistle Brook. One the northern eaves of the region was Woodhall.

column4: and Samwise Gamgee met Gildor Inglorion and his party of wandering elves in the Woody End.

column1: According to David Salo the name means "place at one end of a wood"
column2: representing a possible Old English Wudig Ende.
